"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[501],{8268:function(e,t,o){o.r(t),o.d(t,{ALCHEMIST:function(){return a}});let a={id:"alchemist",title:"The Alchemist Pirate",shortDescription:"A mad scientist experimenting on reluctant crewmates.",skillGrid:{exploration:["star","star","open","star","blocked","blocked","blocked"],brawn:["open","open","blocked","blocked","blocked","blocked","blocked"],hunting:["star","open","open","star","blocked","blocked","blocked"],aim:["star","star","blocked","blocked","blocked","blocked","blocked"],swagger:["star","open","open","open","star","star","blocked"],navigation:["star","open","open","star","star","blocked","blocked"]},constellation:o(9774).k,storyBlanks:[{number:1,prompt:"An exotic ingredient",type:"text"},{number:2,prompt:"A name for your latest potion",type:"text"},{number:3,prompt:"A body part",type:"text"},{number:4,prompt:"A side effect",type:"text"},{number:5,prompt:"The pirate name of another player",type:"player_name"}],backstory:"People call me mad. ME! The greatest alchemical mind of our generation! Simply because a few of my experiments had... unexpected results. So what if the Elixir of {2} turned the duke's {3} purple? It was supposed to do that! Probably! And yes, the incident with the {1} extract did cause a bit of {4} among the test subjects, but that's what informed consent forms are for. Not that any of them could read.\n\nI was expelled from the Royal Academy of Sciences for \"reckless endangerment\" and \"crimes against nature\" and \"making the dean's cat explode.\" Narrow-minded fools, all of them! So I took my brilliance to the seas, where a pirate ship provides the perfect mobile laboratory. Unlimited test subjects — I mean, willing volunteers — and exotic islands full of rare ingredients.\n\n{5} has been particularly helpful as a test subject. Well, not helpful exactly, since they don't know they're a test subject. I've been slipping small doses of my latest formula into their grog. So far the only side effect has been mild {4}, which is actually an improvement over last time.",events:[{narrative:"I found a deposit of pure {1} on the last island! This is the missing ingredient I've been searching for! The formula for my {2} Elixir is nearly complete! I may have gotten a bit overexcited and accidentally set fire to my lab in the celebration, but the {1} is safe!",effect:"Retrieve card 53 Alchemist's Kit from the story deck."},{narrative:"I tested my latest potion on a captured enemy sailor. Results: immediate {4}, followed by a brief period of {3} enlargement, and then — quite unexpectedly — the ability to speak to fish! Not exactly what I was going for, but I'll call it a success!",effect:"Crew +1. Infamy +2."},{narrative:"After weeks of careful experimentation, I've created a compound that makes things explode on contact. The applications are endless! The crew is less enthused, especially after I accidentally demonstrated it on the toilet seat.",effect:"Gain 1 skill of your choice. Discontent +1."},{narrative:'{5} finally noticed the side effects of my experiments. I managed to convince them it was just a common {3} condition from too much sea air. They seemed skeptical, but I offered to make them a "cure" which is actually just more of the same formula. For science!',effect:"Re-roll +2. Treasure +1."},{narrative:"My {2} Elixir is COMPLETE! The greatest alchemical achievement of our time! I drank a small dose myself to prove it's safe. Side effects include: heightened intelligence, mild glowing, and an unfortunate craving for {1}. I consider this a total success!",effect:"Gain 1 skill of your choice. Re-roll +1. Misfortune +1."}],endings:{bad:{threshold:"≤3",text:'Your experiments finally catch up with you when {5} discovers what you\'ve been putting in their grog. The crew holds a trial, and despite your passionate defense of "the advancement of science," you are found guilty of "being a complete menace" and are marooned on a small, barren island with nothing but a cauldron and a single vial of {1} extract. You spend your remaining days mixing mud and seawater, trying to recreate your formulas from memory. The {4} you gave yourself from drinking the {2} Elixir turns out to be permanent. At least the fish talk to you.'},good:{threshold:"4",text:"After your pirating days, you open an apothecary called The {2} Shop, where you sell your potions to anyone brave enough to buy them. Your remedies are surprisingly effective, if somewhat unpredictable. Your cure for the common cold does work, but also causes temporary {4} and turns the patient's {3} green for a week. Despite this, business thrives because your competitors' potions don't work at all. {5} becomes a regular customer, having developed a strange addiction to your formulas. You never do tell them about the grog. Some secrets are better kept for science."},legendary:{threshold:"5",text:"Your {2} Elixir revolutionizes medicine across the known world. Kings and queens seek your expertise. The Royal Academy of Sciences sends you a formal apology and offers you the position of Grand Alchemist, which you accept on the condition that they rename the academy after you. Your experiments become safer (mostly) and your discoveries cure diseases, extend lifespans, and only occasionally cause mild {4}. {5} writes a best-selling memoir about being your unwitting test subject, which becomes required reading at the academy. You eventually create the legendary Philosopher's Stone, which can turn any {1} into pure gold. You could sell it for unimaginable wealth, but instead you use it as a paperweight. Some things are worth more than gold."}}}}}]);